            id: "decorator",
            name: "Decorator",
            intent: "Attach additional responsibilities to an object dynamically. A flexible alternative to subclassing for extending functionality.",
            analogy: "A coffee shop: start with a plain Espresso. Wrap it in MilkDecorator (+$0.50). Wrap that in SugarDecorator (+$0.20). Each wrapper adds behavior and cost without changing the original cup. You stack layers like clothing.",
            when: `When you need to add optional behaviors to objects in combinations — and using inheritance to cover every combination would create too many classes.

Here's the concrete problem. A library book can have: a protective cover, a barcode, or a damage note. Any combination is valid:
• Just a barcode
• Cover + barcode
• Cover + barcode + damage note
• Just a damage note

With inheritance:
class BookWithCover               extends Book { ... }
class BookWithBarcode             extends Book { ... }
class BookWithCoverAndBarcode     extends Book { ... }
class BookWithDamageNote          extends Book { ... }
class BookWithCoverAndDamageNote  extends Book { ... }
// 3 features = up to 2³ = 8 subclasses
// 5 features = up to 32 subclasses

With Decorator: you have one class per feature. You wrap them at runtime in any order, any combination. 3 features = 3 decorator classes, not 8.`,
            howItWorks: `There are four pieces.

PIECE 1 — The Component interface

What every book — plain or decorated — must be able to do:

interface LibraryBook {
    String getDescription();
    double getHandlingCost();
}

PIECE 2 — The Concrete Component (the base object)

The plain book with no extras:

class BasicBook implements LibraryBook {
    private String title;
    public BasicBook(String title) { this.title = title; }

    @Override public String getDescription() { return title; }
    @Override public double getHandlingCost() { return 1.00; }
}

PIECE 3 — The Base Decorator

This is the key structural piece. It implements LibraryBook (so it IS a book), but also holds a LibraryBook reference (so it WRAPS a book). All concrete decorators extend this:

abstract class BookDecorator implements LibraryBook {
    protected LibraryBook book; // the thing being wrapped

    public BookDecorator(LibraryBook book) {
        this.book = book;
    }
    // doesn't implement the interface methods here — subclasses do
}

Why does it both implement AND hold LibraryBook?
• implements LibraryBook → so it can be used anywhere a LibraryBook is expected
• holds LibraryBook      → so it can wrap any book (including another decorator)

PIECE 4 — Concrete Decorators

Each one adds one feature:

class ProtectiveCoverDecorator extends BookDecorator {
    public ProtectiveCoverDecorator(LibraryBook book) { super(book); }

    @Override public String getDescription() {
        return book.getDescription() + " + Cover"; // adds to what's already there
    }
    @Override public double getHandlingCost() {
        return book.getHandlingCost() + 0.50; // adds to existing cost
    }
}

class BarcodeDecorator extends BookDecorator {
    private String barcode;
    public BarcodeDecorator(LibraryBook book, String barcode) {
        super(book); this.barcode = barcode;
    }

    @Override public String getDescription() {
        return book.getDescription() + " [Barcode: " + barcode + "]";
    }
    @Override public double getHandlingCost() {
        return book.getHandlingCost() + 0.20;
    }
}

Usage — stack decorators like layers:

LibraryBook book = new BasicBook("Clean Code");
// description: "Clean Code" | cost: $1.00

book = new ProtectiveCoverDecorator(book);
// description: "Clean Code + Cover" | cost: $1.50

book = new BarcodeDecorator(book, "LIB-001");
// description: "Clean Code + Cover [Barcode: LIB-001]" | cost: $1.70

Each call to getDescription() walks the chain:
BarcodeDecorator.getDescription()
  → calls book.getDescription() (which is ProtectiveCoverDecorator)
    → calls book.getDescription() (which is BasicBook)
      → returns "Clean Code"
    → returns "Clean Code + Cover"
  → returns "Clean Code + Cover [Barcode: LIB-001]"

ORDER MATTERS:
new ProtectiveCoverDecorator(new BarcodeDecorator(book)) → "Clean Code [Barcode] + Cover"
new BarcodeDecorator(new ProtectiveCoverDecorator(book)) → "Clean Code + Cover [Barcode]"
Same components, different order = different result.`,
