            id: "flyweight",
            name: "Flyweight",
            intent: "Use sharing to efficiently support a large number of fine-grained objects by separating intrinsic (shared) state from extrinsic (unique) state.",
            analogy: "A forest in a game has 1,000,000 trees. Each tree has a type (Oak, Pine), texture, and color — these are the same for all trees of that type. Only position differs. Store one Oak object and reference it from a million trees instead of creating a million full objects.",
            when: `When you need a very large number of objects that share most of their data, and storing all that duplicate data in every single object is consuming too much memory.

Here's the concrete problem. A school distributes textbooks. You model each student's copy as an object:

class StudentCopy {
    String subject;    // "Mathematics"
    String publisher;  // "Oxford Press"
    int    pageCount;  // 320
    String studentId;  // unique
    String condition;  // unique
}

For 300 math students, you create 300 StudentCopy objects. Each one stores "Mathematics", "Oxford Press", and 320. That's the exact same three values repeated 300 times in memory. For 10,000 students across 10 subjects, you store the subject metadata 10,000 times.

The insight: subject, publisher, and pageCount are the same for every math student. Only studentId and condition differ per student.

Flyweight says: extract the shared data into one shared object. Each student copy holds a reference to that shared object instead of its own copy.`,
            howItWorks: `The key concept first: intrinsic vs extrinsic state.

• Intrinsic state  = shared, never changes per instance = goes in the Flyweight
• Extrinsic state  = unique per instance = stays in the Context (the per-instance object)

For textbooks:
• Intrinsic:  subject, publisher, pageCount (same for all math students)
• Extrinsic:  studentId, condition (different for each student)

PIECE 1 — The Flyweight (intrinsic state only)

class TextbookType {
    private final String subject;    // intrinsic
    private final String publisher;  // intrinsic
    private final int    pageCount;  // intrinsic

    public TextbookType(String subject, String publisher, int pages) {
        this.subject   = subject;
        this.publisher = publisher;
        this.pageCount = pages;
        System.out.println("Created type: " + subject); // only called once per subject
    }

    public String getSubject()   { return subject; }
    public int    getPageCount() { return pageCount; }
}

PIECE 2 — The Flyweight Factory (pool/cache)

Makes sure you never create two TextbookType objects for the same subject. If it already exists, return the existing one:

class TextbookFactory {
    private static Map<String, TextbookType> pool = new HashMap<>();

    public static TextbookType get(String subject, String publisher, int pages) {
        if (!pool.containsKey(subject)) {
            pool.put(subject, new TextbookType(subject, publisher, pages));
        }
        return pool.get(subject); // always returns the same object for same subject
    }
}

PIECE 3 — The Context (extrinsic state + reference to flyweight)

One per student. Holds what's unique, plus a reference to the shared type:

class StudentCopy {
    private final TextbookType type;  // shared — just a reference, not a copy
    private final String studentId;   // extrinsic — unique
    private final String condition;   // extrinsic — unique

    public StudentCopy(String subject, String publisher,
                       int pages, String studentId, String condition) {
        this.type      = TextbookFactory.get(subject, publisher, pages);
        this.studentId = studentId;
        this.condition = condition;
    }
}

Usage:

for (int i = 0; i < 300; i++) {
    new StudentCopy("Math", "Oxford", 320, "S" + i, "Used");
}
// "Created type: Math" prints ONCE — TextbookType created only once
// 300 StudentCopy objects exist, but all share one TextbookType in memory

Without Flyweight: 300 objects × 3 duplicated fields = 900 field values
With Flyweight:    300 objects × 0 duplicated fields + 1 shared object = way less memory

The savings multiply with scale: 10,000 students across 10 subjects = 1 TextbookType per subject (10 total) instead of 10,000 copies of the same data.`,
