            id: "proxy",
            name: "Proxy",
            intent: "Provide a surrogate or placeholder for another object to control access to it.",
            analogy: "A credit card is a proxy for your bank account. It has the same interface (pay), but adds features: spending limits, fraud detection, transaction logging — without you touching your actual account directly every time.",
            when: `When you want to add behavior — caching, access control, logging, lazy loading — around an existing object, without the client knowing anything changed and without modifying the real object.

Here's the concrete problem. Every time a report generator needs student info, it hits the database:

class ReportGenerator {
    private StudentDatabase db = new StudentDatabase();

    public void generate(String[] ids) {
        for (String id : ids) {
            System.out.println(db.getStudentInfo(id)); // DB hit every time
        }
    }
}

If the same student ID appears 10 times in the report, that's 10 DB queries for identical data. You want to cache results — but you don't want to change StudentDatabase (other parts use it), and you don't want to mix caching logic into ReportGenerator (that's not its job).

You need something that sits between ReportGenerator and StudentDatabase, looks identical to StudentDatabase from the outside, but adds caching internally. That's a Proxy.`,
            howItWorks: `There are three pieces.

PIECE 1 — The Subject interface (shared contract)

Both the real object and the proxy implement this. The client only knows about this interface — it never knows if it's talking to the real thing or a proxy:

interface StudentDatabase {
    String getStudentInfo(String studentId);
}

PIECE 2 — The Real Subject

The actual heavy object — hits the database, does the real work:

class RealStudentDatabase implements StudentDatabase {
    @Override
    public String getStudentInfo(String studentId) {
        System.out.println("[DB] Querying for " + studentId + "...");
        return "Name: Ali | Grade: 10 | GPA: 3.8"; // simulated result
    }
}

PIECE 3 — The Proxy

Implements the same interface as the real object. Holds a reference to it. Adds its own logic before/after delegating:

class CachingStudentProxy implements StudentDatabase {
    private RealStudentDatabase realDB = new RealStudentDatabase();
    private Map<String, String> cache  = new HashMap<>();

    @Override
    public String getStudentInfo(String studentId) {
        if (cache.containsKey(studentId)) {
            System.out.println("[Cache] Returning cached: " + studentId);
            return cache.get(studentId); // skip the DB entirely
        }
        // Not cached — go to real DB and store result
        String data = realDB.getStudentInfo(studentId);
        cache.put(studentId, data);
        return data;
    }
}

Usage — client receives a StudentDatabase. Doesn't know or care if it's real or proxy:

StudentDatabase db  = new CachingStudentProxy();
ReportGenerator gen = new ReportGenerator(db);

gen.generate(new String[]{"S001", "S002", "S001", "S001"});
// [DB] Querying for S001...        ← real DB, first time
// [DB] Querying for S002...        ← real DB, first time
// [Cache] Returning cached: S001   ← no DB
// [Cache] Returning cached: S001   ← no DB

THE FOUR PROXY TYPES — same structure, different purpose:

• Caching Proxy      → stores results, avoids repeating expensive calls
• Protection Proxy   → checks permissions before calling the real object
• Virtual Proxy      → delays creating an expensive object until it's actually needed
• Logging Proxy      → records every call to the real object transparently

All four follow the same structure: same interface, wraps the real object, adds behavior around the call.

HOW PROXY DIFFERS FROM DECORATOR:
Both wrap an object. The difference is intent:
• Decorator → adds new behavior, the client knows it's decorating
• Proxy     → controls access, the client thinks it's talking to the real thing`,
