            id: "strategy",
            name: "Strategy",
            intent: "Define a family of algorithms, encapsulate each one, and make them interchangeable. Lets the algorithm vary independently from clients that use it.",
            analogy: "A navigation app (Google Maps style). Users can choose: drive, walk, bike, or public transit. The app's overall logic is the same — show a route. Only the routing algorithm changes. Each is a Strategy you plug in.",
            when: `When you have a class that needs to perform a task, but there are multiple valid ways to do it — and you want to switch between them without rewriting the class or cramming all variants into one big if/else.

Here's the concrete problem. A bank calculates interest differently depending on account type:

class BankAccount {
    public void applyInterest(String type, int months) {
        if (type.equals("savings")) {
            double interest = balance * 0.04 * (months / 12.0);
            balance += interest;
        } else if (type.equals("fixed")) {
            double rate = 0.07 / 12;
            balance = balance * Math.pow(1 + rate, months);
        } else if (type.equals("current")) {
            // no interest
        }
    }
}

Every time the bank adds a new account type — PremiumSavings, JuniorAccount, IslamicAccount — you open BankAccount and edit applyInterest(). You're modifying code that handles existing, working accounts. Each edit risks introducing a bug in all the other branches.

Strategy says: extract each algorithm into its own class. BankAccount holds a reference to whichever strategy is active, calls it, and never knows the details.`,
            howItWorks: `There are three pieces.

PIECE 1 — The Strategy interface

The contract every algorithm must fulfill:

interface InterestStrategy {
    double calculate(double principal, int months);
}

PIECE 2 — Concrete Strategies

Each one is its own class with its own algorithm. They're completely independent — changing one can't break another:

class SimpleSavingsInterest implements InterestStrategy {
    @Override
    public double calculate(double principal, int months) {
        return principal * 0.04 * (months / 12.0); // simple annual rate
    }
}

class CompoundFixedDepositInterest implements InterestStrategy {
    @Override
    public double calculate(double principal, int months) {
        double monthlyRate = 0.07 / 12;
        return principal * Math.pow(1 + monthlyRate, months) - principal;
    }
}

class NoInterest implements InterestStrategy {
    @Override
    public double calculate(double principal, int months) {
        return 0; // current accounts earn nothing
    }
}

PIECE 3 — The Context

Holds a reference to a Strategy. Calls it when needed. Never contains the algorithm itself:

class BankAccount {
    private double balance;
    private InterestStrategy strategy; // ← reference to current algorithm

    public BankAccount(double balance) { this.balance = balance; }

    public void setStrategy(InterestStrategy s) {
        this.strategy = s; // swap at runtime — no other code changes
    }

    public void applyInterest(int months) {
        double interest = strategy.calculate(balance, months);
        balance += interest;
        System.out.printf("Interest: $%.2f | Balance: $%.2f%n", interest, balance);
    }
}

Usage:

BankAccount acc = new BankAccount(10000);

acc.setStrategy(new SimpleSavingsInterest());
acc.applyInterest(12); // uses savings algorithm

acc.setStrategy(new CompoundFixedDepositInterest());
acc.applyInterest(24); // uses compound algorithm — same account object, different behavior

To add IslamicProfitSharing: write one new class that implements InterestStrategy. Call setStrategy(new IslamicProfitSharing()). Nothing else changes.

STRATEGY vs TEMPLATE METHOD:
Both handle algorithm variation. The difference:
• Strategy  → algorithm swapped via composition (holds a reference) — swap at runtime
• Template Method → algorithm varied via inheritance (override a method) — fixed at compile time

Strategy is more flexible. Template Method has less overhead (no extra object).`,
            advantages: [
                "Swap algorithms at runtime",
                "Isolate implementation details from client code",
                "Replace inheritance with composition",
                "Open/Closed: add new strategies without touching existing code"
            ],
