            id: "command",
            name: "Command",
            intent: "Encapsulate a request as an object, thereby letting you parameterize clients, queue requests, log them, and support undoable operations.",
            analogy: "A restaurant order: you sit down, the waiter takes your order on a slip of paper. The slip is the Command. The waiter doesn't cook — they just submit it. The order waits in queue until the chef is ready. The paper slip can be cancelled, re-queued, or logged.",
            when: `When you need to treat an action as an object — so you can store it, queue it, log it, delay it, or reverse it. The classic trigger is needing undo/redo.

Here's the concrete problem. A teacher edits a timetable. Without Command:

class Timetable {
    public void assign(int day, int period, String subject) {
        slots[day][period] = subject;
    }
}

// Teacher makes a mistake
timetable.assign(0, 1, "Math");
timetable.assign(0, 2, "Science");
// Oops — Science should be on day 1, not day 0

There's no undo. To undo, you'd need to save the entire timetable state before every change — a full copy of the grid. For complex objects that gets expensive. And for rollback with reasons (which specific action to undo?), it gets complicated fast.

Command says: wrap each action in an object. That object knows how to execute itself and how to reverse itself. A history stack stores these objects. Undo just pops the last one and calls undo().`,
            howItWorks: `There are four pieces.

PIECE 1 — The Command interface

Every command must be able to execute and undo itself:

interface Command {
    void execute();
    void undo();
}

PIECE 2 — The Receiver (the object doing the actual work)

This is your Timetable. It doesn't know anything about commands — it just does what it's told:

class Timetable {
    private String[][] slots = new String[5][8];

    public Timetable() {
        for (String[] row : slots) Arrays.fill(row, "FREE");
    }

    public void assign(int day, int period, String subject) {
        slots[day][period] = subject;
        System.out.println("Assigned: " + subject + " → Day" + day + " P" + period);
    }

    public String get(int day, int period) { return slots[day][period]; }
}

PIECE 3 — Concrete Command

Stores everything needed to execute and undo the action. Note it saves the previous state so undo can restore exactly what was there before:

class AssignSubjectCommand implements Command {
    private Timetable timetable;
    private int day, period;
    private String newSubject;
    private String previousSubject; // saved at execute time for undo

    public AssignSubjectCommand(Timetable t, int day, int period, String subject) {
        this.timetable  = t;
        this.day        = day;
        this.period     = period;
        this.newSubject = subject;
    }

    @Override
    public void execute() {
        previousSubject = timetable.get(day, period); // save before changing
        timetable.assign(day, period, newSubject);
    }

    @Override
    public void undo() {
        timetable.assign(day, period, previousSubject); // restore
        System.out.println("  (undone)");
    }
}

PIECE 4 — The Invoker (manages history)

Executes commands and keeps a stack for undo:

class TimetableEditor {
    private Stack<Command> history = new Stack<>();

    public void execute(Command cmd) {
        cmd.execute();
        history.push(cmd); // remember it
    }

    public void undo() {
        if (!history.isEmpty()) {
            history.pop().undo(); // reverse last action
        }
    }
}

Usage:

Timetable tt = new Timetable();
TimetableEditor editor = new TimetableEditor();

editor.execute(new AssignSubjectCommand(tt, 0, 1, "Math"));
editor.execute(new AssignSubjectCommand(tt, 0, 2, "Science"));
editor.execute(new AssignSubjectCommand(tt, 1, 1, "English"));

editor.undo(); // undoes English
editor.undo(); // undoes Science

WHY NOT JUST SAVE THE WHOLE TIMETABLE STATE BEFORE EACH EDIT?
You could. But that's Memento's job — saving and restoring full object snapshots. Command is about action-level undo: each command knows exactly what it changed and how to reverse that one specific change. More efficient, more surgical.

Command vs Memento:
• Command  → undoes by reversing the specific action ("put back what was there before")
• Memento  → undoes by restoring a full snapshot ("revert the whole object to this earlier state")`,
