            id: "iterator",
            name: "Iterator",
            intent: "Provide a way to access elements of a collection sequentially without exposing its underlying representation.",
            analogy: "Different ways to tour Rome: wander on your own, hire a tour guide, or use a GPS app. All three 'iterate' over the sights. The way you traverse is separate from the places themselves.",
            when: `When you have multiple collection types — lists, arrays, trees, linked lists — and you want the code that uses them to work the same way regardless of how the collection stores its data internally.

Here's the concrete problem. A school has two types of rosters: one stored as a sorted ArrayList, another stored as a plain array. A teacher does roll call on both:

class Teacher {
    public void rollCallList(AlphabeticalRoster r) {
        for (String s : r.students) { // accesses .students directly
            System.out.println(s);
        }
    }
    public void rollCallArray(NumberedRoster r) {
        for (int i = 0; i < r.count; i++) { // accesses .students[] directly
            System.out.println(r.students[i]);
        }
    }
}

Two problems:
1. The teacher is coupled to the internal structure of each roster — it knows that one uses an ArrayList and the other uses an array. If AlphabeticalRoster switches to a LinkedList, rollCallList breaks.
2. You need a separate method for every new roster type.

Iterator extracts traversal logic from the collection. Every collection provides an iterator with the same two methods — hasNext() and next(). The teacher calls these and nothing else.`,
            howItWorks: `There are four pieces.

PIECE 1 — The Iterator interface

The standard traversal contract. Every iterator must implement this:

interface StudentIterator {
    boolean hasNext(); // is there a next element?
    String next();     // give me the next element
}

PIECE 2 — The Aggregate interface

Every collection must be able to produce an iterator:

interface ClassRoster {
    StudentIterator createIterator();
}

PIECE 3 — Concrete Collections + their Iterators

Each collection creates its own iterator that knows how to walk through its internal structure:

// ArrayList-based roster
class AlphabeticalRoster implements ClassRoster {
    private List<String> students = new ArrayList<>();
    public void add(String name) { students.add(name); }

    @Override
    public StudentIterator createIterator() {
        List<String> sorted = new ArrayList<>(students);
        Collections.sort(sorted);
        return new ListStudentIterator(sorted);
    }
}

class ListStudentIterator implements StudentIterator {
    private List<String> list;
    private int index = 0;
    public ListStudentIterator(List<String> list) { this.list = list; }

    @Override public boolean hasNext() { return index < list.size(); }
    @Override public String  next()    { return list.get(index++); }
}

// Array-based roster
class NumberedRoster implements ClassRoster {
    private String[] students;
    private int count = 0;
    public NumberedRoster(int capacity) { students = new String[capacity]; }
    public void add(String name) { students[count++] = name; }

    @Override
    public StudentIterator createIterator() {
        return new ArrayStudentIterator(students, count);
    }
}

class ArrayStudentIterator implements StudentIterator {
    private String[] arr;
    private int count, index = 0;
    public ArrayStudentIterator(String[] arr, int count) {
        this.arr = arr; this.count = count;
    }

    @Override public boolean hasNext() { return index < count; }
    @Override public String  next()    { return arr[index++]; }
}

PIECE 4 — The Client (Teacher)

One method. Works with any roster. Never sees the internal structure:

class Teacher {
    public void rollCall(ClassRoster roster) {
        StudentIterator it = roster.createIterator();
        int num = 1;
        while (it.hasNext()) {
            System.out.println(num++ + ". " + it.next());
        }
    }
}

Usage:

Teacher teacher = new Teacher();

AlphabeticalRoster r1 = new AlphabeticalRoster();
r1.add("Zahra"); r1.add("Afif"); r1.add("Sadia");
teacher.rollCall(r1); // 1. Afif  2. Sadia  3. Zahra  (sorted)

NumberedRoster r2 = new NumberedRoster(3);
r2.add("Tom"); r2.add("Ana");
teacher.rollCall(r2); // 1. Tom  2. Ana  (insertion order)

Same rollCall() method. Different internal structures. The iterator hides the difference.

Java already has this built in: every Collection implements Iterable, which returns an Iterator. The for-each loop uses it automatically. This pattern is why for-each works the same on ArrayList, HashSet, LinkedList, and arrays.`,
