            id: "template-method",
            name: "Template Method",
            intent: "Define the skeleton of an algorithm in a base class, deferring some steps to subclasses.",
            analogy: "A school exam: every exam follows the same process — distribute papers → read instructions → answer questions → collect papers. The structure is fixed. The subject-specific instructions and questions vary. Subclasses fill in the subject parts.",
            when: `When you have several classes that do the same thing in the same sequence, but differ in one or two specific steps — and you're duplicating the shared steps across all of them.

Here's the concrete problem. A school runs different exams. Every exam follows the same sequence: distribute sheets → read general instructions → give subject-specific instructions → answer questions → collect sheets. Only steps 3 and 4 differ per subject.

Without Template Method:

class MathExam {
    public void conduct() {
        System.out.println("Distributing sheets...");       // duplicate
        System.out.println("Instructions: 3 hours...");    // duplicate
        System.out.println("Math: use calculator");        // unique
        System.out.println("Solving algebra...");          // unique
        System.out.println("Collecting sheets...");        // duplicate
    }
}

class ScienceExam {
    public void conduct() {
        System.out.println("Distributing sheets...");       // duplicate
        System.out.println("Instructions: 3 hours...");    // duplicate
        System.out.println("Science: label diagrams");     // unique
        System.out.println("Writing experiments...");      // unique
        System.out.println("Collecting sheets...");        // duplicate
    }
}

If the general instructions change, you update every exam class. If the sequence changes (say, add an attendance check before distributing), you update every exam class. For 10 subjects, that's 10 edits for one change.

Template Method puts the sequence in one place — the base class. Subclasses only fill in the parts that differ.`,
            howItWorks: `There are two pieces.

PIECE 1 — The Abstract Class with the Template Method

The template method defines the sequence. It's marked final so subclasses can't reorder or skip steps. Common steps are implemented here. Variable steps are declared abstract — subclasses must provide them:

abstract class ExamProcess {

    // THE TEMPLATE METHOD — sequence is fixed, marked final
    public final void conduct() {
        distributeSheets();          // common — implemented here
        readGeneralInstructions();   // common — implemented here
        giveSubjectInstructions();   // varies — subclass fills this in
        answerQuestions();           // varies — subclass fills this in
        collectSheets();             // common — implemented here
    }

    // Common steps — no need for subclasses to touch these
    private void distributeSheets() {
        System.out.println("Distributing answer sheets...");
    }
    private void readGeneralInstructions() {
        System.out.println("Instructions: No talking. 3 hours. Blue pen only.");
    }
    private void collectSheets() {
        System.out.println("Collecting answer sheets...");
    }

    // Abstract steps — subclasses MUST implement these
    protected abstract void giveSubjectInstructions();
    protected abstract void answerQuestions();
}

Why private for common steps and protected abstract for variable steps?
• private → only the template method can call them; subclasses can't accidentally override them
• protected abstract → subclasses can see and must implement them, but outsiders can't call them directly

PIECE 2 — Concrete Subclasses

Each only overrides the two steps that are specific to it. The sequence, distribution, and collection are inherited and never duplicated:

class MathExam extends ExamProcess {
    @Override
    protected void giveSubjectInstructions() {
        System.out.println("Math: you may use a calculator. Show all working.");
    }
    @Override
    protected void answerQuestions() {
        System.out.println("Students solve algebra, geometry, calculus...");
    }
}

class ScienceExam extends ExamProcess {
    @Override
    protected void giveSubjectInstructions() {
        System.out.println("Science: label all diagrams. Units are mandatory.");
    }
    @Override
    protected void answerQuestions() {
        System.out.println("Students write definitions, experiments, diagrams...");
    }
}

Usage:

new MathExam().conduct();
// Distributing answer sheets...
// Instructions: No talking. 3 hours. Blue pen only.
// Math: you may use a calculator. Show all working.
// Students solve algebra, geometry, calculus...
// Collecting answer sheets...

new ScienceExam().conduct();
// Distributing answer sheets...       ← same, from base class
// Instructions: No talking...         ← same, from base class
// Science: label all diagrams...      ← unique to ScienceExam
// Students write definitions...       ← unique to ScienceExam
// Collecting answer sheets...         ← same, from base class

Adding EnglishExam: extend ExamProcess, override two methods. Zero changes to base class.

HOOKS (optional steps):
Sometimes a step shouldn't be required — just optional. You can provide a default empty implementation instead of abstract:

protected void beforeCollecting() {
    // default: do nothing
    // subclasses can override if they need extra time warnings, etc.
}

Subclasses that need it override it. Those that don't, ignore it. This is called a hook method.`,
