            id: "interpreter",
            name: "Interpreter",
            intent: "Define a grammar for a language and provide an interpreter to deal with that grammar.",
            analogy: "A musician reading sheet music. The notation is the grammar — quarter notes, rests, dynamics are defined rules. The musician is the interpreter who reads the symbols and produces sound. Every symbol maps to a concrete action defined by the grammar.",
            when: `When you have a set of rules or expressions that can be combined in different ways, and you want to evaluate them without hardcoding every possible combination.

Here's the concrete problem. A school has honor roll eligibility rules. Today the rule is: GPA >= 3.5 AND absences <= 5. Without Interpreter:

class HonorRollChecker {
    public boolean isEligible(double gpa, int absences, int grade) {
        return gpa >= 3.5 && absences <= 5 && grade >= 10;
    }
}

This works — until the rules change. Next semester the rule is: (GPA >= 3.5 AND absences <= 5) OR scholarship == true. You edit HonorRollChecker. The semester after: different rules for different grade levels. Each change requires a code edit and redeployment.

More importantly, different schools or different contexts need different rules. Hardcoded rules can't be composed at runtime — they're fixed at compile time.

Interpreter says: represent each rule as an object. Combine them using AND, OR, NOT objects. The final rule is a tree of objects that you evaluate by calling interpret(). Change the rules by changing how you assemble the tree — no code edits needed.`,
            howItWorks: `There are three kinds of pieces: the Expression interface, Terminal Expressions (the leaf rules), and Non-Terminal Expressions (the combinators — AND, OR, NOT).

PIECE 1 — The Expression interface

Everything — individual rules and combinations — implements this:

interface RuleExpression {
    boolean interpret(Map<String, Object> context);
}

context is a Map holding the data being evaluated — in this case a student's GPA, absences, grade.

PIECE 2 — Terminal Expressions (leaf rules)

These are the atomic conditions. Each checks one thing:

class GpaExpression implements RuleExpression {
    private double minGpa;
    public GpaExpression(double min) { this.minGpa = min; }

    @Override
    public boolean interpret(Map<String, Object> context) {
        double gpa = (double) context.get("gpa");
        return gpa >= minGpa; // true or false
    }
}

class AbsenceExpression implements RuleExpression {
    private int maxAbsences;
    public AbsenceExpression(int max) { this.maxAbsences = max; }

    @Override
    public boolean interpret(Map<String, Object> context) {
        int absences = (int) context.get("absences");
        return absences <= maxAbsences;
    }
}

class ScholarshipExpression implements RuleExpression {
    @Override
    public boolean interpret(Map<String, Object> context) {
        return (boolean) context.get("hasScholarship");
    }
}

PIECE 3 — Non-Terminal Expressions (combinators)

These combine other expressions. They hold references to sub-expressions and delegate to them:

class AndExpression implements RuleExpression {
    private RuleExpression left, right;
    public AndExpression(RuleExpression l, RuleExpression r) { left=l; right=r; }

    @Override
    public boolean interpret(Map<String, Object> context) {
        return left.interpret(context) && right.interpret(context);
        // both sub-expressions must be true
    }
}

class OrExpression implements RuleExpression {
    private RuleExpression left, right;
    public OrExpression(RuleExpression l, RuleExpression r) { left=l; right=r; }

    @Override
    public boolean interpret(Map<String, Object> context) {
        return left.interpret(context) || right.interpret(context);
    }
}

class NotExpression implements RuleExpression {
    private RuleExpression expr;
    public NotExpression(RuleExpression e) { this.expr = e; }

    @Override
    public boolean interpret(Map<String, Object> context) {
        return !expr.interpret(context);
    }
}

Usage — build the rule as a tree of objects:

// Rule: (gpa >= 3.5 AND absences <= 5) OR hasScholarship
RuleExpression rule = new OrExpression(
    new AndExpression(
        new GpaExpression(3.5),
        new AbsenceExpression(5)
    ),
    new ScholarshipExpression()
);

Map<String, Object> afif = Map.of("gpa", 3.8, "absences", 2, "hasScholarship", false);
System.out.println(rule.interpret(afif)); // true — GPA and absences pass

Map<String, Object> sadia = Map.of("gpa", 2.9, "absences", 8, "hasScholarship", true);
System.out.println(rule.interpret(sadia)); // true — scholarship saves it

Map<String, Object> karim = Map.of("gpa", 2.5, "absences", 6, "hasScholarship", false);
System.out.println(rule.interpret(karim)); // false — nothing qualifies

To change the rule next semester — just rebuild the tree differently. No class changes.

THE TREE STRUCTURE:
           OrExpression
          /            \
    AndExpression    ScholarshipExpression
    /          \
GpaExpression  AbsenceExpression

interpret() is called on the root. It recursively calls interpret() down the tree and combines results on the way back up.

WHEN NOT TO USE IT:
Interpreter is good for simple grammars (a handful of expression types). If your grammar has 20+ expression types or needs performance, use a proper parser generator (ANTLR, JavaCC) instead. Interpreter trades flexibility for simplicity — it's not meant for parsing full programming languages.`,
